single_game_results.explain: The game is composed of two components. First, dodgeballs need to land both inside and on top of a bin that's a hexagon shape. Second, cube blocks need to moved.
single_game_results.overall: The instructions seem to be pretty straightforward.   It doesn't seem too easy or too hard ... it's just right. I think I would like this game if I was looking for something that was fun and not too difficult.

single_game_results.explain: First, you need to place the hexagon bin near the wall. Then, you need to throw golfballs and make sure they either stop on the bin or go inside the bin.  You also need to stack the blocks so you have 3 on top, with one block being the same as the one it's resting on.
single_game_results.overall: This games seems slightly more difficult that the prior game, because you are throwing golfballs at the target rather than dodgeballs. Also, you have to do a bit more with the cubes.  However, I still think it's rather fun and not too hard.

This game is more challenging than the prior two.  I feel that there is a lot of restrictions in this game.  I also don't like that you lose points if the ball doesn't go in the bin. That seems like it might take some of the fun away.
single_game_results.explain: First, you need to put the bin next to the bed and remove what is currently on the bed.  Then, stand by the desk and throw various types of balls to get them in the bin.  In this game, you lose points if the ball doesn't land in the bin.
Place the bin next to the wall.  Throw balls to get them in the bin.
single_game_results.overall: This game has the simplest instructions. One can just have fun playing this game and not have to worry about restrictions or losing points.  It's a good game to play if you just want to have fun and not have to follow so many rules.

single_game_results.explain: Move chairs and then let them go so they end up on a desk and still able to move with you holding it.
single_game_results.overall: I don't like this game.  I don't really understand how the chair would end up ON a desk unless you lifted it up there.  I can't really visualize how this game would work exactly.
I think this game would be too hard.  It's hard enough to get the ball in the bin, but to have to touch the ramp first, seems to add a component that makes it difficult.
single_game_results.explain: First, place the bin near one of the ramps. Throw a ball and make sure it touches the ramp and then goes inside the bin.  Keep playing until the bin is no longer upright.
Throw dodgeballs around making sure that they don't land inside the dog bed.
single_game_results.overall: This game would be pretty boring.  It's mainly just throwing a ball around.  It seems like it would be really easy to avoid the dog bed, so there's nothing challenging about it at all.

single_game_results.explain: This game has two components. First, throw cube blocks but you lose points if they come to a stop. Second, put Cd's and credit cards inside the bins.
single_game_results.overall: The part about putting the credit cards and CD's in the bin is very easy, but very boring. It's like cleaning. The part about throwing the blocks and not having them come to a stop, seems too difficult. It seems like every block that is thrown would eventually stop, so that part of the game is a bit confusing to me.

single_game_results.explain: Place the bin near the rung. Then, throw balls aiming for either inside the bin or on the doggie bed.
single_game_results.overall: I think I would like this game.  It's very straightforward and doesn't have too many rules or restrictions.  It's seems doable, with just the right amount of challenge.

The part about throwing the balls into the bin seems fun.  I'm a bit unclear about throwing them so they stop moving. I would think that all the balls would stop moving within a few seconds of being thrown into the bin.
single_game_results.explain: Throw balls to get them inside the bin and stop moving.

debrief_responses.strategy: I considered how easy or difficult it would be to play, how many rules there were to follow and if I understood what was expected in the game play.  I personally like games that are a bit challenging, but not too much, so I feel like I can succeed at the game.  If a game has too many rules to follow, I wouldn't find it as enjoyable.

single_game_results.explain: Two "targets" are the foundation of the game which includes the dog bed and hexagonal bin. The goal is to throw the ball at either the dog bed or bin and have it lad and rest on either of these two targets. Points are earned by successful landings.
single_game_results.overall: I think this game can be quite boring after awhile. Initially it also doesn't sound that fun but may be attention getting initially because it's something new. But the game play itself isn't that creative or challenging.

single_game_results.explain: A ball is thrown anywhere and you earn a point when it lands. But if the ball lands on the dog bed, you lose 3 points. The goal would be to just throw the ball and have it land anywhere but the dog bed.
single_game_results.overall: This game is boring and there really is no point. The ways to earn a point is far too easy and not challenging. The game is lacking any real sort of barriers or obstacle to make it fun.

This game lacks fun game play. To stay in place and just throw a ball at a bin feels very repetitive and quite boring. While it may be challenging to have the ball land exactly on the bin, it just doesn't seem fun to do this just to earn a point.
single_game_results.explain: Place the hexagonal bin near the rug. This stays there and is the foundation to the game. The goal is to earn a point by throwing the dodgeball and have it land on the top of the bin.

There are 3 ways to earn 1 point. One is to pick up the green triangle block and put it down. The other way is to throw the dodgeball towards the desk and have it land on the desk. Lastly, throwing the basketball and having it land on the hexagonal bin.
single_game_results.overall: The game is quite boring. Especially how it's very easy to earn a point given that all you have to do is pick up and put down the triangle block. If that's all you have to do to earn a point, then it's not challenging at all. The other two methods are more challenging but isn't that interesting either.

I like that there's an element of different points for more difficult actions, but the actions themselves are quite boring. This lack of challenging goals makes the game seem like it would get tiring real soon.
single_game_results.explain: Place different objects around the room including a hexagonal bin near the center of the room. Near this bin is a ball. Then throw a teddy bear so that it lands on the bin or it touches the ball. When it lands on the bin, 5 points are earned. If the teddy bear touches the ball, 1 point is earned.

Make sure all objects are stationery. Then roll a golf ball towards the rug. The goal is to either get the golf ball to stop near the rug or have it land on the rug and stop. One point is earned for when either of these two goals are met.
single_game_results.overall: This game isn't even a game. A point is earned if a golf ball lands near the start of the rug or on the rug. It's way too simple and easy. There's no challenging aspect of this game to make it interesting.
This is not a game. There's no challenge to it. There is literally nothing to this "game" except putting things on something and then not receiving any points for doing this action.
single_game_results.explain: The player places a credit card or CD inside the hexagonal bin. No points are given.
The rug is the line where the player throws a ball from. The goal is to throw 10 balls into the hexagonal bin. Every time the balls lands inside the hexagonal bin, a point is earned.
single_game_results.overall: This game actually feels like a game. There is a challenge to it which is to get as many balls as you can inside the hexagonal bin. While it may be somewhat challenging, I think it is quite repetitive and can be boring after awhile.

This game is boring. There is nothing to do. If there is no time limit and no barriers to earning a point, there's really no point in playing this game. It's too easy to just place any object on the bin and earn a point.
single_game_results.explain: Place the hexagonal bin in the middle of the room. Then either throw or place objects in this bin in the center of the room. Any objects that are inside the bin are 1 point.
The goal is to throw the dodgeball at either the side table, the bed or hexagonal bin. A point is earned when the ball lands on either of these items (table, bed and bin).
single_game_results.overall: The game is too simple but a bit challenging. Having a limited number of balls and trying to get it to land on top of different objects can be challenging. But there is an element that makes it quite boring which is the bed. Having the ball land on the bed is very easy because the bed is quite large and will also take in the shock of the throw. So while there's a challenge aspect to it, it's too easy.

debrief_responses.strategy: My strategy was to see how challenging the games were. If the game play is boring, pointless and too easy, it's not even a game to me. The whole point of a game is to have it be challenging and make you think. When the games didn't do this, then my evaluation of the game was low.

It seems like a very boring game, as the design isn't setup to be fun. It's more like a math problem than it is a game, especially with the environment provided. My overall impression would be negative.
single_game_results.explain: It is a game described as putting balls into a bin, which is multiplied by 3 times the amount of CDs/credit cards/pencils placed inside the top drawer. It's a mathematical equation given inside a game.

single_game_results.overall: My overall impression is that it is dependent on the rug and distance from it, which is a tad underdeveloped. The idea of it being near a rug isn't bad, but since there isn't a specificity on distance, the game is less fun and hard to understand, which hurts enjoyment and wanting to replay it.
single_game_results.explain: You're moving items closer to a rug, but making sure they are not moving themselves. Each point is earned for each item that is near a rug, but staying still.

single_game_results.overall: I think the flexibility of where you can throw these balls makes the game much more humanistic and interesting overall, which is different from previous studies. I'd find it more enjoyable and see others as feeling the same, despite some of the rules, such as time, not being as prevalent for the game.
single_game_results.explain: You are essentially trying to get dodgeballs to land on a specific surface, such as bed, and you receive a point per surface. There are multiple given, so the user may have to remember these instructions to ensure of the points received by the end of the game.

You can get an infinite amount of points for dodgeballs thrown, while placing items in a bin can exponentially increase the points in a faster space of time. You get 40 points per dodgeball in a hexagonal bin, while it is multiplied by credit cards and CDs in the bin.
single_game_results.overall: My overall impression is that the game is a bit too complicated to play, as it has too many different items given. I find simpler projects to be more fun, but the inclusion of the dodgeball's point system could be the variable on how enjoyable it is for myself and others. It is a game that seems like it's mildly interesting when a person controls the ability to do moves, as well, as watching this wouldn't be enjoyable.

My overall impression with the game is that it would be very enjoyable, despite the difficulty being a bit easier. I think the bin being aligned with the wall allows for easy shots, like shooting a basketball off the backboard, but it would be something that is more humanistic and fun to play. Many users would aim to score high, and that could provide a competitive edge.
single_game_results.explain: You're aiming to stand on the rug and put dodgeballs and blocks into the hexagonal bin, which gives you a point or 2, depending on the item. You're not going to be aiming at the most level structure, due to the bin being on top of a desk, but it should be aligned with the wall.

single_game_results.overall: My overall impression of this game is negative, simply due to the extra items we must follow as players. It is a bit confusing, but the statement about the dodgeball needing to rest is what led me to not finding this as enjoyable. I see it as an extra option, but making it mandatory just removes a bit of the fun from the game, while making it unwatchable for a spectator.
single_game_results.explain: Essentially, the game revolves around ball placement with the dodgeball. You get a point for each time you land one inside, or on top of, the hexagonal bin. It is stated as it must be resting, so it must meet this criteria.

Each dodgeball that lands in a bin that is stabilized on a bed or wall is given 3 points, while a player receives 1 for each that bounces off the floor before entering the bin. The hexagonal bin still remains, but it must be placed in one of two spots, and has to remain there for the duration of the game.
single_game_results.overall: My overall impression of this game is positive, but that's due to the scoring system. It prioritizes having fun, while the point system makes the most sense, as a successful throw rewards more. Therefore, users will feel more inclined to go for 3, which creates more competition, as the bounce from the floor adds another mechanism for scoring too. I don't see any real issues with the way this game is set up, although, others might.

single_game_results.explain: The point of this game is to throw dodgeballs for a point, which is given when they land and stop on 2 objectives. There are no other ways of scoring, so the users must focus on getting this item placed on doggie beds and hexagonal bins.
single_game_results.overall: My overall impression is that the game has a good foundation, but it is not as interesting when played versus watching someone play. I believe that the dodgeball having to land on top of items restricts a bit of the creativity, but it can be competitive still.

single_game_results.explain: You're supposed to get a point for each ball that is in a position within, or on top of, a bin, while dodgeballs increase the score by following that format, but giving 5 instead. The bin is placed next to the door as you throw, so it is not balanced on any sort of structure.
single_game_results.overall: My overall impression of this game is very positive, just because of how simple it is. The focus on needing to get specific types of balls in certain positions is what adds to the fun, and it is something I could see school children utilizing when bored. Therefore, it does a lot more with much less, and that's the advantage it has over other games.

This game is positive to me, because it is pretty simple overall, along with the scoring system. Nothing goes above and beyond, but the simplicity makes me believe that a majority of people would find it a bit more stimulating overall than some complex games in this reality. The usage of teddy bears can add to the difficulty, but it is a physics-based encounter with the pillow that gifts a fun challenge.
single_game_results.explain: This game revolves around the finite amount of times you can throw teddy bears onto pillows, where you get a point for each that lands and doesn't move on a pillow.

debrief_responses.strategy: I just utilized the strategy of comparing it to games I play, or played, as an adult and child. Using old experiences to compare to the descriptions of each game provided me with a place of comparison, which was the strategy. Essentially, games have to be more childlike than complex to get a rise out of most people, while allowing for rules to be understood. Therefore, those usually received higher ratings overall.

single_game_results.explain: The game is basically a makeshift game of cornhole where the player must set up the bin next to the desk and a ramp leading into the bin. Above the ramp would be the desk which contains the computer. The player would go to the opposite side of the room and throw objects such as the blocks and balls, into the hex bin. There is small room for error to get points because your target point is a bin opening and having too high of a trajectory will cause it to land on the desk to lose 1 point. Different objects give different points. The golfball however must touch the ramp before going into the bin, so I would assume rolling it up the ramp into the bin would be wise.
single_game_results.overall: Very basic game. Again, it's basically makeshift cornhole with extra steps. I'm not a fan of using the different blocks like the pyramids and triangles and would rather just use the balls. And I think the ramp and desk make it a bit too complicated.

single_game_results.explain: The game is a point based game of placing objects in areas of varying difficulty to get more points. Areas/goals are established such as the bin, shelf or floor. Then the player tries to place them in their respective areas for points.
single_game_results.overall: It's a fairly simple game. But I very lackluster in the competitive and skills department. I'm assuming placing objects doesn't mean throwing them from a point and means physically laying them on their respective places. That would mean the only real skill based action would be throwing the ball onto the bin.

single_game_results.explain: Place the hex bin near the door. Then from a specified distance, throw a golfball or dodgeball from your position into the bin to score points.
single_game_results.overall: Simple game. Just shooting balls into a bucket. However, linking back to learning the virtual environment interaction, I'm assuming the ball stays on top if its too big meaning that to win the game to get most points, you would have to use golfballs first before the dodgeball as to not plug up the hole.

single_game_results.explain: You are going to throw various types of balls having them land and stop on specific targets. The balls used will be golf balls, basketballs, and dodgeballs. single_game_results.overall: This game would be challenging, but fun to play. It is easy to understand
single_game_results.explain: You are going to place a curved wooden ramp on the rug and throw a beachball so that it rolls on the ramp and comes to rest on the rug. The rug has the colors pink, yellow , orange, green, purple, and white. You will lose a point each time the beachball lands on white. you will get 1 point if it lands on pink, 2 points if it lands on yellow, 3 for orange, and 3 for green.

You are going to place the hexagonal bin on an empty bed and throw dodgeballs, basketballs, and beachballs aiming to get them into the bin. You will lose 1 point for each ball that does not land in the bin. You will get 10 points for each dodgeball that makes it into the bin, 20 points for each basketball, and 30 points for each beachball.
single_game_results.overall: This game would be fun to play. It is easy to understand the directions.

single_game_results.explain: You are going to place a hexagonal bin near the door. single_game_results.overall: This game is a little confusing but would be fun to play. It would be better to watch someone else play this game first and play it yourself.

single_game_results.overall: The basketball task sounds very hard, and it's not connected to placing the chairs on the desks. I don't understand why they're part of the same game.
single_game_results.explain: After moving the hexagon bin onto the rug, throw basketballs and attempt to land them on top of the bin. You get 40 points for doing this. You can also get 1 point for each chair you put on a desk.

Pick up any cube block and set it down anywhere inside a building. You must do this at least 3 times to end the game. Your score is the number of times you've placed a cube block in a single building.
single_game_results.overall: The game ends when three blocks have been moved and there only seems to be one building, so I think everyone/every attempt would have the same score (three). This does not seem fun to me. Also, all the cubes are already in the building, so it does not even feel like you are accomplishing something.
It seems like the ball would be able to do more than those two things and it would look silly if those are the only ways it can move.
single_game_results.explain: After putting the curved wooden ramp in the middle of the room, pick up a pink dodgeball. Attempt to throw the dodgeball so it touches the ramp and lands on the bed. If you do not succeed, it will bounce back and hit you. Your score is your number of successes minus the times the ball bounces back at you.
Pick up the cube blocks! You can throw each block for one point. Or, for 15 points, you can set the block down, pick it up a second time, and set it down again in the exact same place.
single_game_results.overall: The different options feel related to each other and make it more fun! You can be precise for more points or chaotic for fewer points.
It's basic, but that's not a bad thing
single_game_results.explain: Throw the dodgeballs into the hexagonal bin. You'll get one point for each ball that lands and stays in the bin.
Throw as many dodgeballs as you can! You'll get a point for each dodgeball you throw.
single_game_results.overall: There are no instructions on how long you have to throw dodgeballs. When does the game end?
Which door? Should the hexagon bin be on top of a ramp, meaning the ball is rolling up a ramp? I'm really not sure how to make this work.
single_game_results.explain: After putting the hexagon bin by the door, roll dodgeballs down the rug so they land in the bin. You'll get a point for each attempt, plus 5 extra points for every success!

single_game_results.overall: The multiplier is fun, although it just seems so weird to deliberately throw dodgeballs at a bin full of CDs.
single_game_results.explain:
Aim dodgeballs at the horizontal bin. Landing them inside is worth 40 points, although you'll get 1 point for throwing each ball even if you don't succeed.

You can also move credit cards or CDs into the hexagonal bin to increase your score! Your points for successful throws will be multiplied by the number of credit cards and CDs in the bin.

During this game, you can move a variety of items. You can throw balls into the hexagonal bin. You can put credit cards, CDs, and pencils into the bin. You can also place the credit cards, CDs, and pencils into the top drawer.

You will EARN one point for each of the credit cards and CDs in the hexagonal bin. But you will LOSE three points for each ball inside the bin, each credit card and CD not collected, and each credit card, CD, and pencil in the top drawer. You will neither gain nor lose points for pencils in the bin or not collected.
single_game_results.overall: If the player knows the exact scoring rules in advance, the scoring rules are pointless. If the player doesn't know the exact scoring rules in advance, they should be told that some of the tasks will earn points and some will lose points, or they will feel cheated.

single_game_results.explain: Throw dodgeballs into the hexagon-shaped bin! You'll earn one point for each ball that lands and stays in the bin.
single_game_results.overall: It's simple but it could be fun

debrief_responses.strategy: I tried to figure out whether or not the game would be interesting and seemed like games most people already play such as basketball. If a game had confusing instructions such as stacking blocks a particular way than I tended to evaluate it lower because there are then more rules to follow which further complicates the game making it harder to follow and play and it makes the game confusing because some of the tasks were tedious yet worded in a way that made them seem confusing (such as stacking blocks and making sure two are the same type). I also assessed whether or not the game would sustain my attention and help move me around in the game environment which would help me get better acquainted with the room I'm playing the game in.

single_game_results.overall: It sounds interesting, but it also sounds like just cleaning. I mean, it would be fun to incorporate a points system into cleaning, perhaps leading to higher productivity, but as far as this being a game, it doesn't sound too fun.

It sounds like an interesting game, but I'm not sure what they mean by when the object stops moving. 
I mean, the ball is going to move when it falls into the bin or the bed, but how long does the player wait for it to stop moving?
Should it just be a dead fall?

single_game_results.explain: Start by placing a hexagonal bin or a doggie bed somewhere in the room. The player can earn a point for each dodgeball that stops moving inside the bin and a point for when the ball stops moving inside the doggie bed.

single_game_results.overall: This one sounds incredibly complicated and I'm not sure I fully understand what they want to achieve with the rules. I feel that this game could be a good one, if it were more clear and less convoluted.
single_game_results.explain: To begin, the player stacks blocks in a certain configuration. They receive a point for each stack where one cube block is placed atop another block, with a tall rectangular block on the same cube. In another instance, players can earn a point for each stack where a cube block is atop a tall, rectangular block, which is on top of another cube block, with an additional cube block on top, provided the bottom block is the same type as the tall, rectangular block. Further, players will earn a point for each stack where a tall, rectangular block is atop a cube block, which is atop a cube block, and the top cube block is the same type as the third cube block. The final score is calculated from the sum of these three configurations.

single_game_results.overall: This game sounds interesting, but as an adult, I'm not sure I want to stack blocks for imaginary game points. It would be fun, if someone was really bored, I'm sure, but it seems repetitive and monotonous. Perhaps a game that would only be played a few times before boredom set in.
single_game_results.explain: In this game, the player begins by stacking a flat block on a bridge block, and the placing a tall, cylindrical block on the flat block. From there, they stack a cube block atop the tall, cylindrical block, and a pyramid block on the cube block. Once that setup is complete, players can earn 10 points for every different set of clocks they have successfully stacked in this order by the end of the game.

In this game, the player begins by stacking three blocks on top of a tall, rectangular block, with two stacked blocks being the same type as the tall, rectangular block. Scoring is 1.4 times the number of stacks the player has at the end of the game.
single_game_results.overall: It sounds like more block stacking to me, and as an adult, this doesn't really appeal to me. I suppose games like Jenga and such are also stacking games, but they seem more involved and entertaining. Plus the scoring system sounds like it would take a bit of math to know how well you're doing.

single_game_results.explain: In this game, the player throws dodgeballs in such a way that they land atop the desk or rest on top of the hexagonal bin. Players get a point for every ball that stops on the desk and 20 points for every dodgeball that stops inside and on top of the hexagonal bin.
single_game_results.overall: I think that this game sounds somewhat fun, though might be a bad idea to be throwing balls at a desk. It feels like this could be a little destructive if the player does not aim well enough. It seems challenging, as well, that you get more points depending on where the ball comes to rest. This one sounds also like it might be fun to play with other people, as well.

single_game_results.explain: In this game, the player is instructed to stand next to a hexagonal bin and throw balls to get them to land inside of the bin. The game ends after the player has taken 5 throws with the balls or as soon as they successfully throw a ball which lands in the bin. The player will earn 5 points for each ball that successfully is thrown into the bin.
single_game_results.overall: It sounds like a pretty decent game, but it might be too easy, considering the game ends after a ball reaches its goal of inside the bin. It seems like it could just be throwing balls into a bin and scoring for however many land. Perhaps this game would be fun, also, when playing with more than one person. It feels like it could be a competitive game!

I'm not so sure as I understand this one, but there doesn't seem to be a lot to it. Do CD points cancel out credit card points? Is the end goal to get zero points? I know I personally have more CDs than credit cards, so it could be a little biased in some instances, for example.
single_game_results.explain: In this game, the player begins by placing credit cards or CDs into a hexagonal bin. They will score zero points regardless of the number of objects in the bin. These objects add to and subtract from the score equally, cancelling each other out.

In this game, a player sets a dodgeball near his or her desk before beginning the game. They then throw the dodgeball so that it touches the south wall while it is still in motion, making sure that the ball is not being held while in motion. The game ends after 60 seconds and the player receives 1 point for each time they successfully throw the dodgeball and it touches the south wall, and then stops moving.
single_game_results.overall: I think this game sounds like a good one! But, personally, I would struggle knowing which wall is south. I feel that this game would be easy to learn and might take a few tries to get good at it, but it would be fun to spend a few minutes on.

single_game_results.explain: Throw balls into a hexagonal bin to get points. You get more points for each dodge ball inside the bin.
single_game_results.overall: The game is really simple, but is confusing in that why would you ever use the ball that scores less points.
The game makes no sense in that why would you ever want to land balls into the bin. You would purposefully miss to not get points penalized.
single_game_results.explain: You're to throw golf balls into the hexagonal bin while stacking cubed blocks. You get points based on following guidelines for stacking blocks minus four times the amount of golf balls you land inside the bin.

Throw balls and land them in a bin while standing next to the desk. You get points for landing each ball into the bin, with the amount of points varying by ball type. You lose points for each ball that misses.
single_game_results.overall: The game makes sense and has a clear win state. The penalties are fair, making it a kind of fun game.

single_game_results.explain: Throw a beachball and try and have it roll on the ramp and end up stopping on the rug. The various parts and colors of the rug determines how many points you gain or lose.
single_game_results.overall: The game is really engaging and fun sounding, and would be something that I would find myself actually playing. The instructions are clear and fair.
The game is really simple and kind of boring. You just move balls from one spot to another for points.
single_game_results.explain: You get points by putting different balls on the bed.

single_game_results.overall: The game is pretty confusing and required reading multiple times. It seems way too complicated.
single_game_results.explain: You get points for stacking blocks in a specific kind of way. Your final points are based on the different set configurations.
Move objects around and avoid having the objects anywhere near the doggie bed.
single_game_results.overall: The game is really simple and is just moving things around with extra steps. There's no actual gamification of the process as there's no points or penalties.
The game is really simple and easy to do, but would get pretty repetitive fast.
single_game_results.explain: Throw a dodge ball into the hexagonal bin and get one point for each successful attempt.
Throw dodge balls into the bin for one point each. You also move the cube blocks in certain arrangements for one point each.
single_game_results.overall: The cube aspect is really confusing, and the ball and cube stacking don't really make sense in the context of the rest of the game.

single_game_results.explain: Place a bin on the rug and throw a dodge ball so it bounces off the top shelf and lands in the bin. You get a point for a each dodge ball that both hits the shelf and lands in the bin.
single_game_results.overall: The game is fun sounding as it adds an element of trying to figure out where the ball would land after throwing it at something else. There's a sense of randomness.

single_game_results.explain: The game consists on throwing a ball inside a bin. You earn one point each time the ball goes into the bin.
single_game_results.overall: I think the game is rather simplistic, since you earn just one point no matter how far you are from the bin. Maybe it'd be good for very young children.
I thought the game was strange. The choice of the dog bed as one of the landing spots seemed very arbitrary.
single_game_results.explain: The goal of the game is to throw a ball and have it land inside a bin, "on top" of said bin, or on a dog bed. You earn one point each time you succeed with any of the conditions.

single_game_results.overall: I thought the game has a slight challenge, overall it can be enjoyed by everyone.
single_game_results.explain: The game consists on throwing balls into a bin 10 times while standing on a rug. Your final score is the number of balls inside the bin after 10 throws.

The goal of the game is to throw balls into a bin, move cube blocks on a top shelf, and throw pillows on a dog bed. One point is earned for each ball, cube, and pillow that meets the above conditions.
single_game_results.overall: The ball throwing part is fine, but the rest is just too confusing to be fun.

single_game_results.explain: I think the game consists of two challenges: to toss objects so that they land as close to the rug as possible, and toss balls around. You earn a point for each object that ends nearest to the rug, and one point each time you throw a ball.
single_game_results.overall: I thought the game doesn't make sense at all. Where am I supposed to stand? What's the point of tossing balls? What was even the point of the bin being by the door?

single_game_results.explain: The game consists on placing balls on the bed. You get one point per ball placed on the bed.
single_game_results.overall: I think the game is extremely simple. It'd be good for a toddler or otherwise a very young child to help get familiarized with the concept of "placing something on X surface."
I thought the game is far too complicated to be fun, and potentially dangerous with stacking chairs on top of a desk.
single_game_results.explain: I think the game consists of four challenges: placing chairs on desks, putting pens or CDs inside a bin, throw balls on a bed, and stack blocks in a certain sequence. I cannot make sense of the scoring system, though.

The goal of the game is to throw balls and land them on specific targets depending on the ball type. Golf balls that aren't white should go inside the bin, basketballs or white golf balls on the top shelf, basketballs in a bin, dodgeballs in a bin. The scoring system is one point per each golf ball that lands in the bin, and honestly can't understand the rest of it.
single_game_results.overall: The scoring system is too complicated to be fun.
I thought the description was too vague, and I'm not sure I correctly interpreted it.
single_game_results.explain: I think the game objective is to toss objects so that they land as close to the rug as possible, presumably from the opposite side of the room. The game ends in three minutes, and your final score is the number of objects that landed closest to the rug at the end.

single_game_results.overall: I thought it was a tad too simplistic, but fun game for young children.
single_game_results.explain: The goal of the game is to throw balls around the room, but avoid a dog bed. You earn one point for each ball that has been thrown and is no longer moving; you lose three points for every ball that ends up on the dog bed.

single_game_results.explain: You need to place a hexagonal bin by the rig and make sure it stays there for the entire game. Hold a dodgeball to throw it in the bin, where you earn 1 point for each time you succeed at it.
single_game_results.overall: It seems like it would be fun to test my throwing accuracy! I would love to try it out.

single_game_results.explain: Put a hexagonal bin by a rug and leave it there the whole game. What you need to do is put cellphones or CDs in there, and get 2 points for each of those in the bin at the end of the game.
single_game_results.overall: It seems like a fun challenge. I would like to get as many items in the bin as possible!

single_game_results.explain: Earn 1 point each time you land a dodgeball either inside or on top of a hexagonal bin when it stops moving!
single_game_results.overall: This seems like a nice challenge. Getting the dodgeballs to stop makes it extra fun!
This seems like a nice game to play. It has the potential to be a game that you can play for hours on end.
single_game_results.explain: The top drawer needs to be empty at some point and you need to place different things in there and close it. You get 1 point for each item at the end of the game that is in there!

single_game_results.overall: This seems very hard to learn. That, however, will make it such an intriguing game!
single_game_results.explain: Put the chairs on the desks, pens and CDs in the hexagonal bin, dodgeballs on the bed, and stack two cube blocks on a tall rectangular block that is on top of another cube block of the same type. Your score will be determined by adding all of the successfully completed individual previously named tasks and multiplying that by two.

single_game_results.overall: This seems like a nice way to determine accuracy. The individual landing instructions made it even more fun overall!
single_game_results.explain: Make sure you leave a hexagonal bin near the door for the entire game and throw golf and dodge balls either on top of or inside the hexagonal bin. Your final score will be the entire sum of the successful throws of golf balls that stop on top of the bin, dodge balls that stop inside of the bin, and dodge balls that stop on top of the bin.

Near the side table, all golf balls, dodgeballs, triangle blocks, and pyramid blocks need to be placed. You need to make sure that there is no chair that is directly in front of the desk for the entire game. A curved wooden ramp with its front adjacent to the front of the desk and a hexagonal bin that has its front facing the back of the ramp need to be positioned. These items must be kept there for the entirety of the game. As you stand by the bed, you need to throw the golf balls, dodgeballs, triangle blocks, or pyramid blocks either in a hexagonal bin or touching a laptop/desktop computer. If you toss a golf ball, it needs to make contact with the curved wooden ramp before landing in the bin.
single_game_results.overall: This is extremely hard. The unique rules for each of the four items makes it so much fun to get to play!
This is a nice game with multiple steps. While not too hard, it seems very fun.
single_game_results.explain: A curved wooden ramp needs o be placed next to a hexagonal bin and remain together throughout. Grab and throw a dodge ball so it makes contact with the curved wooden ramp before landing in the hexagonal bin. You get 1 point each time a dodge ball successfully stops in the bin and makes contact with the curved wooden ramp.

single_game_results.overall: The game seems rather fun. The challenge of the blocks seems especially fun!
single_game_results.explain: Every blue cube block needs to be placed on the rug while ensuring they remain there for the whole game. You need to move objects around the room. You get 5 points every time an object is not moving and is near the north wall, as well as just 1 point for every stack where there is a yellow cube block of the same type as a blue cube block sandwiched between two other cube blocks.

single_game_results.overall: The game seems like a great test of accuracy. I would love to play it!
single_game_results.explain: A dodge ball needs to be placed near the desk before beginning, and you need to throw the dodge ball so that it connects with the south ball while moving, while making sure that you are not holding it or a teddy bear as it moves. The game lasts for 60 seconds. 1 point will be awarded to you for each time you get a dodge ball to stop moving after touching the south wall.

single_game_results.overall: I am very confused about the purpose of the objects near the rug and how you score points with them. I don't understand  why they need to be moved near the rug and how the 70 points scored for the objects are related to the dodgeballs on the rug. I'm having a hard time visualizing this game.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to throw a dodgeball into a hexagonal bin. While throwing dodgeballs, you will also score based on how many objects you have near the rug and whether they are moving.

single_game_results.overall: This doesn't seem like a game to me. The only real objective of the game is to move a chair onto the desk. The 1 point for moving a teddy bear is insignificant that it can be ignored. The hexagonal bin near the rug is also pointless.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to move chairs and teddy bears on desks. The teddy bears cannot be positioned diagonally. Each chair is worth 80 points and each teddy bear is worth 1 point. During the game, a hexagonal bin must remain near the rug.

The objective of the game is to move chairs onto a desk. You get 4 points if the chair is still moving when you let it go on the desk and 1 point if the chair is not moving. The game ends when you score 10 points.
single_game_results.overall: This game seems fun, but I'm having a hard time understanding between a moving chair and a non-moving one. If there was a way to release the chair that keeps it moving on the desk, I would think it is easy to replicate so it would be easy to score 10 points that way.

single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to place objects in either hexagonal bins or into the top drawer. Balls can be thrown into the bin while credit cards, CDs, and pencils can be placed in either bin or top drawer. Your score depends on where and how many of each object is placed.
single_game_results.overall: I'm very confused by the scoring for this game. I think this is less of a game and more of a math optimization problem. I don't understand it at all.
I think this game is simply and easily enjoyable by many. It is essentially a mini basketball hoop in the room and scoring requires practice and skill.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to throw basketballs and dodgeballs into a hexagonal bin that has been placed near the north wall and will remain stationary. Each dodgeball scored is worth 1 point and each basketball scored is worth 0.1 points.

The objective of this game is to throw dodgeballs and tan cylindrical blocks at a hexagonal bin. Dodgeballs need to land on top of the bin while the blocks need to land inside. Each correctly placed object is worth 1 point and you can get an additional 6 points for each dodgeball that lands on top of the bin.
single_game_results.overall: I think this is a fun and challenging game. I think scoring the blocks inside the bin would be relatively easy, but most of my focus and fun would come from getting multiple dodgeballs to land on top of the bin.

This game is confusing for how points are scored. It also seems quite boring as you are just standing in one location. I don't think it involves a lot of thinking or skills. I would think most people would just try to score the 5 points each time.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to move different objects on and off the bed while standing next to a desk. Your score depends on where the objects are located and whether they are moving.

single_game_results.overall: I'm not sure what the objective of throwing the dodgeballs into the hexagonal bin is if you are penalized in points for scoring them. It would make sense to ignore them or intentionally miss to prevent losing points, which makes the game pointless.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to throw dodgeballs inside the hexagonal bin while stacking cube blocks. Each successful cube block stacks will score you points and you will lose points based on how times you land a dodgeball in the bin.

The objective of the game is to throw a dodgeball inside a hexagonal bin. You can throw the dodgeball from different locations marked by three different colored pyramid boxes. You can score different amount of points based on where you decide to throw from. Additionally, you can also score points by building structures using the pyramid blocks and a cube block.
single_game_results.overall: This game seems like it is appropriately challenging and requires a fun amount of skill and strategy. I think the point scoring is a bit confusing because there are so many ways to score points. However, I think this is part of the game and needs to be incorporated into the strategy.

I think this is straightforward and simple game of a mini basketball hoop. I don't think there is much strategy here except choosing  to focus more on the balls that score more points. I'm not sure what the point of having no teddy bears or pillows on the bed is. That doesn't affect this game at all and how it is played.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to throw balls inside the hexagonal bin while standing next to a desk. You score 10 points for each dodgeball that lands in the bin, 20 points for each basketball and 30 points for each beachball. Each ball that doesn't land in the bin will lose you 1 point.

debrief_responses.strategy: I evaluated each game based on how easy I could imagine myself playing the game. If the rules were easy to understand, I would picture myself trying to play and whether I needed to play each game differently each time or if each round I played would be the same and repetitive. If the rules were hard to understand, I automatically evaluated the game negatively since I wasn't able to imagine myself playing the game correctly.

single_game_results.overall: The game is fun because I play with 3d shapes, colors, counting, and stacking. With various and many objects, toys, balls and blocks there are many ways to be creative and joyous for the objectives and results. I would be happy to share and play this game with others.
single_game_results.explain: With this game, the setup is simple, the gameplay is challenging yet rewarding, and the scoring is complex. To begin, the hexagonal bin is to be placed on the rug, dodgeballs ready to throw in the bin, while one bridge block is placed on the floor to stack as many cube blocks on top and at least one is blue. To play, I have to throw dodgeballs into the bin, then stack cube blocks onto the bridge block. When I have thrown all of the dodgeballs and stacked as many cubes as I can onto the bridge block, I add up the number of cube blocks stacked onto the bridge block minus 4x as many dodgeballs that went into the bin.

The setup includes a flat block placed on the rug as to not move as I gain points to build structures in gameplay with the flat block and a cube block to earn 10 points for each object used. Also, three pyramid blocks are arranged on the floor with one hexagonal bin in a square format as I play and score by throwing dodgeballs into the hexagonal bin while standing next to each pyramid. To continue, I earn the most points when I throw three consecutive dodgeballs into the bin next to the blue pyramid. Additionally, I earn the most points when I include three cube block objects with the flat rock structure.
single_game_results.overall: The task that includes the flat block and cube block to build structures would be challenging because I cannot move the flat block. The task that includes throwing dodgeballs into the bin would be most fun and rewarding because I have to develop skills to aim the balls into the bin because my score depends on how many dodgeballs I am able to throw into the bin.

This game would be simple and easy but fun because the instructions are not too complex and confusing. I would aim to throw as many dodgeballs into the bin as possible but would be anxious to see how many dodgeballs pounce out by bouncing off of other dodgeballs.
single_game_results.explain: The gameplay and scoring are easy to understand and accomplish. I am to throw dodgeballs into the hexagonal bin to score one point for each one that stops moving while inside and on top of the bin.

single_game_results.overall: The skill to throw dodgeballs in the bin is hardest and has the lowest outcome of points scored at one point for each dodgeball in the bin. However, for each object that is not moving near the rug for the game equals 70 times how many dodgeballs are on the rug rather than thrown into the bin.
single_game_results.explain: The gameplay and scoring of this game is unique and the scoring does not depend on skills, rather my willingness and space of objects and dodgeballs I can place on the rug. Objects and dogeballs are placed near the rug as I get one point score to throw dodgeballs into the hexagonal bin. Additionally, I get 70 points for number of objects are near the rug times dodgeballs left on the rug rather than thrown into the bin.

single_game_results.overall: This task would be easy because it includes limited objects but it would be challenging because there are only so many objects that would fit onto the doggie bed.
single_game_results.explain: The setup, gameplay, and scoring is simple and only include a doggie bed and as many objects I can place on the doggie bed. The doggie bed is placed near the rug as I get one point for as many objects I can place on the doggie bed.

single_game_results.overall: This game would be challenging because it would be difficult to get the golf ball and dodgeball to stay on top of the hexagonal bin while it would be more easier to just throw the dodgeballs into the bin to score.
single_game_results.explain: The gameplay and scoring in this game is simple to include only golf balls, dodge balls and a hexagonal bin. The gameplay id to throw golf balls and dodge balls aiming to land on top of the bin. I score one point for each dodgeball that stops inside the bin while gaining one point for each golf ball and dodge ball that stops on top of the bin.

To begin, the green golf ball and a dodgeball are placed near the door for the duration of the game. The gameplay includes throwing dodge balls and objects into the hexagonal bin while standing next to the green golf ball near the door. I score 10 points for each object I can throw into the bin as I throw dodgeballs into the bin but the game ends when I miss throwing same dodgeball into the hexagonal bin more than once.
single_game_results.overall: This game would be fun because I would have to try hard to make each dodgeball into the bin by the second throw while throwing as many objects into the bin as possible to score more points.

This game would be fun and unique but would cause a mess to clean up afterwards and may cause objects to unfortunately break. I would find as many objects to drop on the bed until I run out of room including objects that gain more points.
single_game_results.explain: The gameplay is to drop objects onto the bed while standing next to a desk as I score more points for dropping a chair, laptop, and doggie bed that lands on the bed. I score less points for other objects but there are many more of those objects to choose from. I lose points when objects do not land on the bed.

single_game_results.overall: This game would be easy but difficult as I try to find three objects to include a cube block and flat block with two of the same type of cube block for each successful stack.
single_game_results.explain: The setup is to place all green bridge blocks on the rug, while the gameplay is to stack a cube block and flat block on top of another block as the same type of the cube block to get 6 points for each required stack.
The setup is to place a hexagonal bin near the rug as I throw dodgeballs into the bin or on top of the desk. The scoring is summed up by each dodgeball I can throw into the bin or onto the desk.
single_game_results.overall: This task would be easy but difficult. It would be easier to throw the dodge balls into the bin rather than onto the desk because there is a high likely chance that the dodgeballs would bounce off of the desk.

debrief_responses.strategy: While evaluating the games I read the descriptions, located the required objects and placements, thought about how I would score points during gameplay with the required rules and objectives. I tried to imagine playing each game as I felt involved, engaged, challenged, and making sure I understood how to gain the most points rather than lose.

debrief_responses.strategy: I read the description very closely and tried to be very clear when I wrote out the instructions. Any game that I don't understand won't be fun. Then I looked at the gameplay actions. Holding a block and putting it back down again isn't fun. Throwing a block at a bin might be fun.
debrief_responses.comments: These were some super weird games y'all.

single_game_results.explain: Throw golf balls and dodgeballs at the bin. You get points if either kind of ball stops on top of the bin. You also get points if the dodgeball goes inside the bin.
single_game_results.overall: Throwing a ball is as classic as it gets. It doesn't sound very interesting.

single_game_results.explain: Throw cube-shaped blocks (anywhere?). Place yellow blocks inside building blocks. Stack building blocks on top of each other.
single_game_results.overall: This is very confusing. What does the pyramid have to do with anything? Where are you supposed to throw the blocks? Do you get points regardless of where they land? What's a building and what's the difference between a building and a block?

single_game_results.explain: You get 3 points for picking up a block, setting it down, and picking it back up again without moving. You get 1 point for throwing the block onto the rug.
single_game_results.overall: Bizarre. It's very odd that you get the highest points just for picking up a block and putting it back down again.

single_game_results.explain: Stack 4 blocks on top of each other. 3 of the blocks must be tall and rectangular.
single_game_results.overall: My nephew is 3 and he plays this irl. I don't understand the appeal and it sounds even more boring as a video game.

single_game_results.explain: Stack blocks in the this exact order: bridge block, flat block, tall cylindrical block, cube block, and pyramid block on top. You get points for each correct stack of blocks.
single_game_results.overall: This doesn't sound entertaining for adult humans.

Weird again. It's confusing that you can apparently throw a cube block anywhere and get points regardless of where it lands. It's also super weird to just pick a block up and down and get points for that.
single_game_results.explain: There are multiple ways to earn points. 1. Pick up a green triangle block, drop it, and then pick up it up again. 2. Throw a cube block anywhere. 3. Throw a dodgeball into the hexagonal bin.
There are multiple ways to earn points. 1. Put a chair on a desk. 2. Throw a golfball so it lands on a desk. 3. Throw  a dodgeball into the hexagonal bin. 4. Stack 3 cube blocks on top of each other.
single_game_results.overall: This is odd but at least there's a target for each action.
It's a basic throw-object-at-the-target game. The ramp part is confusing. The game doesn't actually use it as a ramp, just as an obstacle.
single_game_results.explain: Put a ramp next to the desk and a hexagonal bin at the bottom of the ramp. You get 1 point for throwing the triangular block in the bin, 2 points for throwing a pyramid block or dodgeball in the bin, and 3 points for throwing a golfball in the bin. You get an extra 3 points if the golfball touches the ramp before landing in the bin. You lose 1 point if an object touches a computer.

single_game_results.overall: This isn't a game; this is just cleaning. It's all kind of random but I guess it's good that there are several different kinds of activities.
single_game_results.explain: There are multiple ways to earn points. 1. Put a chair on a desk. 2. Put a pen or CD in the hexagonal bin. 3. Throw a dodgeball onto the bed. 4. Stack blocks in this order: cube block, tall rectangular block, cube block, cube block.

single_game_results.overall: This was very confusing. I'm still not sure if I understand it. The primary actions are holding blocks and throwing them at nothing while also putting some in a building? I can't tell from the pictures what a building is.
single_game_results.explain: Set up the blocks so that one building has 6 different objects in it. Pick up one block from outside the building and one block from inside the building. Touch the blocks together. Throw the one that was in the building. Put the other block in the building but do not stack it. Set up another building with 6 different objects in it that are not stacked.

single_game_results.explain: Throw as many objects into the bin. Each object is worth one point.
single_game_results.overall: It seems very simple. A game appropriate for children.
The instructions are not specific enough. Is it every block thrown in general or every block thrown in the bin?
single_game_results.explain: Throw the blocks and place the CDs and credit cards in the bin. You earn one point for every credit card or CD you put in the bin, but you lose one point for every block thrown.
Throw a dodgeball on the bin. If it lands you earn a point.
single_game_results.overall: It seems simple and easy. Wish there were some obstacles.
I don't understand the point system. I don't care for the game.
single_game_results.explain: Place chairs on desks and throw the basketballs in the bin. You earn one point for every chair and 40 points per basketball.
stack the same block 3x and have the golf balls land on and inside the bin. Point values are unknown but you only earn points on the blocks
single_game_results.overall: The instructions are no clear. I would NOT want to play this game.
This game seems simple. I like it.
single_game_results.explain: Throw the dodgeballs in the bin. You earn 1 point for the dodgeballs that land inside and on top of the bin.
Throw the dodgeballs in the bin. You earn a point for the balls that stop moving in the bin.
single_game_results.overall: Why do you earn a point if the balls stop moving in the bin? Are they going to jump out? Instructions unclear.

single_game_results.explain: Throw any ball inside the bin and earn a point. You only have 15 attempts though.
single_game_results.overall: If the game was timed it would be much more fun to play.

single_game_results.explain: Earn one point for each dodgeball that lands in the bin.
single_game_results.overall: Very simple. Great children's game.

single_game_results.explain: Throw balls all around the room but be careful because you lose 3 points for each dodgeball that lands on the dog bed.
single_game_results.overall: There is more variety, so one would not get bored as fast. Not bad.

debrief_responses.strategy: I wanted to know what the obstacles were, if any. Throwing a ball seems simple, but there were no other factors to make adrenaline or excitement levels rise. If it's about learning motor skills the games are great.

debrief_responses.strategy: When looking at each game, I thought about how much fun I would have playing it and how much it made sense as a game. As with a lot of games, there should be a good goal for the game and good gameplay to go with it. Therefore, if the game was simple to understand and had good gameplay, I thought it was a good game.

single_game_results.explain: I will place a chair in the center of the room and keep it there for the rest of the game. Then, I will throw dodgeballs to land in different areas of the room. If I land the ball in the bin, I get 5 points, 1 point on the bed, and 1 point on the chair. I will lose 1 point if it lands anywhere else in the room. When I reach a score of 10 points or higher, the game ends.
single_game_results.overall: I think the game is very simple and would be fun for the first few times. I think the scoring could be done better since it ends at 10 points which is not that much.

single_game_results.explain: Place credit cards or CDs in a bin. The scoring will always be 0 since they cancel each other out.
single_game_results.overall: This does not sound like a good game at all since there is basically no scoring and no point in playing the game.

single_game_results.explain: After placing a bin near the rug, hold a dodgeball and throw it to land on top of the bin. For each ball that lands on the bin, you score 1 point.
single_game_results.overall: I think this game is too simple and would get boring very fast. Also it does not make much sense gameplay-wise since if one ball lands on the bin, how would you have more land on the top at the same time?

single_game_results.explain: Throw various balls to land and stop on specific targets. The scoring will depend on various different factors such as which ball is thrown and where and how many throws you can make successfully.
single_game_results.overall: I do not know how the scoring works because it is too complicated, which makes the game sound a lot less fun to play. I do not like it.

single_game_results.explain: Place a bin near the east wall and keep it there. Throw dodgeballs within the goal and try to get them to stop inside the hexagonal bin. The score will be determined by the total number of throws plus 70% of the throws where the ball lands inside the bin.
single_game_results.overall: I think this game and simple and sounds fun. The scoring system is pretty simple and the gameplay sounds fun.

I think this game makes sense for the most part. The scoring part doesn't make much sense since I would assume all the balls stop moving after being thrown. This would mean you just throw the ball anywhere and you will get a point.
single_game_results.explain: Throw dodgeballs so that they land on the doggie bed or bin or stop moving. 1 point for each ball on the dog bed, 1 point for each ball on a bin, and 1 point for each ball that stops after being thrown.

single_game_results.overall: This game is somewhat simple and the instructions make sense. The scoring is not that good and does not make too much sense in terms of being fun and interactive. Sounds kind of boring.
single_game_results.explain: Throw balls and place credit cards or CDs into a bin. For each ball that goes into the bin, multiply this by the number of credit cards or CDs in the bin and add 1 point for each ball thrown.

Place a bin near the rug. Throw dodgeballs into it, on the bed, on the desk, or on top of the bin. For each throw that gets the ball to stop in these spots, get 1 point. Add all points up for the score.
single_game_results.overall: I like this game. The scoring is simple and easy to understand. The gameplay is also simple and makes sense.
I think the game sounds okay and like a game. The gameplay and scoring makes sense for the most part. I would like this game but would not play it for long.
single_game_results.explain: Place a bin near the center of the room. Move objects into the bin by picking them up or setting them in motion. For each different object that is moved into the bin by the end of the game you score 1 point.

Place all balls on the desk, put the bin on the bed, and keep them there. Stand next to the desk and throw balls into the bin. After throwing  the balls 5 times, the game ends. Your score at the end is determined by each ball that stops moving inside the bin.
single_game_results.overall: I think this game does not make much sense and has a lot of steps that do not add up. The scoring is definitely the weirdest part and should be different. I would not like this game.

debrief_responses.aids: I did not use any external aids. I stayed within my own brain and opinions, really looking at each game to form the most accurate opinions.
debrief_responses.techDifficulties: No, everything in the study loaded fine and ran smoothly.
debrief_responses.comments: Interesting study! Glad I could help out with your research. Thanks and have a great day! :)
debrief_responses.strategy: I evaluated the different games based on how fun they looked, whether they would keep me entertained, and the rules/scoring/conditions of each one. "Broken" games are no fun; games that don't make sense, are convoluted, or are too hard or too easy. The optimal games for me are a palatable balance of strategy and skill with a bit of luck thrown in to ensure variation and replayability.

single_game_results.explain: This game is like trick-shotting. The ol' classic of utilizing hand-eye coordination to judge a distance and try to land the object being thrown at or on a certain target.
single_game_results.overall: I used to do this a lot in my youth. It was a lot of fun then, less so now, but still is somewhat. For younger people and those who enjoy trick shots, I'd say this would be pretty fun. It's a basic game, but an enduring classic for a reason.

single_game_results.explain: This game requires a ball, a ramp-like object, and a mat or rug with different color patches on it. The objective of the game is to throw the ball so that it rolls on the ramp and stops at a certain point on the rug. Different colored squares represent different point values in either gains or losses.
single_game_results.overall: This game would be difficult for me personally, trying to get the amount of momentum correct for the ball to stop on the colored square with the highest point value. It's again a basic game that wouldn't hold my attention for long now at my current age, but for younger people, I imagine they would be excited learning to control their throws to try to score points. It reminds me a little of bowling and trains similar skills.

single_game_results.explain: In this game, place a hexagonal bin near the rug in the open space of the room and grab a dodgeball. Throw the dodgeball and try to land it inside the bin. Each successful land of the ball inside the bin equals 1 point earned. Retrieve the ball and try again.
single_game_results.overall: This game is very easy and can be done with most any container and throwable object that won't break. I would get bored of this game pretty quick as I believe I could nail most every throw.

single_game_results.explain: In this game, throw a dodgeball so that it lands either inside a doggie bed, a hexagonal bin, or simply wait until it stops moving after being thrown. Gain 1 point for any of the actions described above.
single_game_results.overall: This game's scope is too broad. The player can score points for doing basically everything and there is no clear objective to focus on. It is basically just "throw the ball and wherever it lands, you score points." That is super boring.

single_game_results.explain: Setup a cured wooden ramp next to a hexagonal bin, making sure that the two objects stay together for the entire game. Grab a dodgeball and throw it so that it touches the ramp and then lands inside the bin. You earn 1 point every time the dodgeball touches the ramp and then lands inside the bin.
single_game_results.overall: This game, I think, would be pretty fun. Depending on how far away from the setup I am when throwing, I would have to calculate force, speed, and angles, bringing in some geometry. Something like this would keep me entertained for an afternoon and would be great for a party game.
This game is a mess and all over the place. The instructions contradict each other and are confusing. The gameplay and win conditions don't line up properly.
single_game_results.explain: Set up a hexagonal bin and grab a red dodgeball. Throw the ball into the bin without it touching the floor. The game ends after throwing the dodgeball 10 times or as soon as it has successfully made it into the bin. You score 5 points if the ball makes it into the bin at least once, 2 points if you can get it into the bin within 5 tries, and 3 more points if you can get the ball into the bin on the first try.

single_game_results.overall: The instructions for this game would be annoying to carry out as it is like rearranging the entire room for no good reason. The other objects in the room as well have no clear relation with the bin and the ball, and this game is unnecessarily complicated and not fun. It is creative though, I will say that.
single_game_results.explain: Place a hexagonal bin near the door. After that, move objects around the room to specific locations: the top shelf, near the floor, and at the north wall. Once that is done, the objective is to throw dodgeballs so that they land still on top of the hexagonal bin. Your final score is the sum of all the points from moving the objects to different locations around the room and for each dodgeball that lands on the hexagonal bin.

single_game_results.overall: Placing chairs on desks is such a random element to a game that it is almost comical. I definitely wouldn't recommend a game like this is real life and even in this virtual space, I'm immediately taken out of the immersive experience to laugh at the absurdity.
single_game_results.explain: Put a hexagonal bin near the rug and ensure it stays in its spot throughout the game. Place the chairs in the room on the desk and then throw basketballs so they land on top of the bin. For every chair on a desk, earn 1 point. For every basketball that stops moving on top of the bin, earn 40 points.

single_game_results.overall: Once again, this game involves geometry and angles and I like it. Very good for training spatial awareness and reasoning. As long as nothing is getting knocked off the shelf by the force of the ball, this would be a fun game to move the bin around between sets and practice throwing the ball at different angles.
single_game_results.explain: Grab the hexagonal bin and put it near the rug, making sure it stays there for the duration of the game. Hold a dodgeball and throw it so that it banks off the top shelf and then lands and rests on the hexagonal bin. You earn 1 point for every dodgeball that successfully touches the shelf and then stops on top of the bin.

In this game, throw both golf balls and dodgeballs, aiming to land them on top of a hexagonal bin. You score 1 point for every dodgeball that stops inside the bin and 1 point for every ball of either type that lands and stops on top of the bin.
single_game_results.overall: The game itself is pretty standard, but the points system is a little off. There should be different point values, rather than every action all yielding the same amount of 1 point.

debrief_responses.strategy: I tried to consider various scenarios within the game space. I tried to think of it from the perspective as a e-sports game, educational game, or just a casual fun experience to kill some time. I applied these avenues into each game which allowed me to better process the creativity or difficulty that would take place.

single_game_results.explain: We must throw objects into a bin. Each object has a different value which is determined by the number of dodgeballs that you've also thrown within that round.
single_game_results.overall: I think that the game has somewhat of a base in terms of what to use, but it's not really fully developed in terms of the objective of the game once it begins. I'm not really certain if my aim is to have the objects land inside the bin or to just hit the top of the bin.

single_game_results.explain: Try to get as many dodgeballs onto the shelf as possible by throwing them and have them land and stay.
single_game_results.overall: This seems like a very easy game to grasp, but a very difficult one to master. It reminds me of those bottle flipping games that's captured a lot of younger crowds on social media. I think it's decent, but the difficulty would probably detract a lot of gamers over time.

single_game_results.explain: Try to throw the dodgeballs into or onto the bin, or on the dog bed.
single_game_results.overall: I think it's a fun game, but without a timer it can lead to people stopping before any particular score is tallied. I think the ease of this game might attract a very young demographic, but for anyone older I think the lack of difficulty would bore others.

single_game_results.explain: Try to get a specific object into a specific destination. Balls must land inside the bin, cube blocks should land on the top shelf, and pillows should be in the dog bed either by toss or direct placement.
single_game_results.overall: I think that game described sounded a bit enticing with the challenge (but not impossible) objective of throwing the ball and the cube into their respective locations. However, the game became too easy when we were given the option to just simply place the pillow into the dog bed. I think to maintain a level of challenge, all objects should remain in a throw state and not allowed to be placed as that should be defined as cheating.

single_game_results.explain: Stack blocks into directed bridge designs to earn points that is based around the color of the stacked block. To earn the most points, you're objective is to aim for flat gray blocks to stack. Otherwise, you can play it safe and throw a dodgeball that will earn you 1 point every time they stop bouncing around.
single_game_results.overall: Perhaps it's my lack of visual understanding of the game, but I'm not really sure that there's any sort of endpoint here. While I like the idea of differentiating point values based around our design abilities, I'm not really sure what consequences or gains of the dodgeball being used since I can get 1 point with the bridge design objective.

single_game_results.explain: After placing the bin by the rug and shelf, your objective will be to throw the dodgeball ensuring that it touches the shelf before landing on top of the bin. You get 1 point for every successful toss that leads to this action.
single_game_results.overall: I think this game would be easy to explain to someone and even easier to grasp. However, I think this game would lead to a lot of frustrations for the players as they develop the skill to pull of the action. This game seems like it can foster a lot of competition which would drive that frustration, but not the game's design itself which I think makes for a great game.

I think this game is clear-cut in its understanding and overall objective. This might be something that some of us experienced as a carnival game or in other video games. I like the idea of having 2 ways to score points that both require different levels of skill. It feels fair and approachable overall.
single_game_results.explain: After we place the bin near the rug, it must not move. Our two items are tan blocks and dodgeballs. For each block that lands into the bin we get 1 point, and for each dodgeball that lands on top of the bin we also get 1 point. Your overall score is these two-point totals combined.

single_game_results.overall: I love games like this as they provide a lot of variety with a pretty minimal layer of randomness. Small things can add up in each throw which I think will have people pulled in and immersed as they play trying to be their last high score! My favorite one so far.
single_game_results.explain: Place the wood ramp next to the rug for setting up the game space. The objective of the game is to grab a beachball and throw it so that lands onto the ramp and rolls onto the rug. Your score is determined by the ball's location on the rug which is broken down as zones of the rug. The zone's points range from 1 to 4 point, including one where can you also lose 1 point if it lands on one of those six zones.

single_game_results.overall: Overall, I believe I somewhat understand the objective of the game, but it doesn't really sound that difficult or entertaining. I'm not really sure how I could be holding the ball I threw or why I would hold a teddy bear within this game, so it'll be easy to gain points and not really lose any which makes the game feel less challenging.
single_game_results.explain: Stand near the desk with a dodgeball. Your objective is to throw the dodgeball, so it hits the south wall and stops afterward. You'll have 60 seconds to hit the south wall where you'll earn 1 point for each stopped dodgeball that accomplishes this.

Your objective will be to hit the wall with a ball and to then follow up with some sort of contact with that ball before it lands. To earn points, you MUST either catch it or touch AFTER it touches a wall. You'll earn 1 point if you accomplish this successfully.
single_game_results.overall: I like the idea of having to move around so the notion of throwing the ball then having to rush to make contact with it after it hits a wall can be the side effect of a little workout. Also, it sounds like a pretty fun mindless game not very competitive but can instead incorporate teamwork as a cooperative mode. It doesn't sound hard, but it still can be a good time.
